1.v: An example SHACL file in Excel
This Excel file shows how to edit simple SHACL shapes in an Excel file

0.v: This sheet specifies the NodeShape with their targets
For details on the conversion process, see the online documentation :

1.v: Label for the Shape (English. Labels in other languages can be added by adding extra columns and adjusting the "@xx" language code

2.v: Textual description of the Shape, in English

3.v: rdf:type. This needs to be either sh:NodeShape, or "sh:NodeShape, rdfs:Class", in which case it means the shape is implicitly targeting all instances of its own URI (so the URI in column A must be the URI of the class, e.g. foaf:Person)

4.v: URI of the targetClass of the shape. Leave empty if the rdf:type is set to "sh:NodeShape, rdfs:Class"

5.v: Type that the nodes controlled by this Shape must have

7.v: Order in which Shape shall be printed

8.v: Background color used to display the shape in diagrams. Can be an hex code or a color name.

9.v: Regular expression that the nodes controlled by this Shape must follow

10.v: Example of URI for targets of that shape. This is printed in the documentation.

11.v: Whether the shape operates in closed world

12.v: Properties to ignore when testing for closed world constraint (a list, always containing rdf:type)

2.v: A Person, whether dead or alive, real or imaginary.

0.v: This sheet specifies the property shapes of the node shapes that are defined in the first sheet

1.v: NodeShape to which the constraint is applied (a reference to a NodeShape IRI from the first sheet)

2.v: Predicate or path on which the constraint applies

3.v: Name of predicate/path in the context of that NodeShape, to be used to display in documentation .

4.v: Description of the predicate/path within the context of that NodeShape

5.v: Use this column to track comments

6.v: Minimum cardinality that the predicate/path must have

7.v: Maximum cardinality that the predicate/path must have

8.v: Type of nodes that the values must have (ususally sh:IRI or sh:Literal)

9.v: For literal values, the expected datatype of the values. If you put more than one, this will be automatically wrapped into a sh:or.

10.v: Expected class that the values of the predicate/path must have.  If you put more than one, this will be automatically wrapped into a sh:or.

11.v: If needed, expected shape that the values of the predicate/path must follow. This must be a reference to a URI of NodeShape from the first sheet.  If you put more than one, this will be automatically wrapped into a sh:or.

12.v: The shape that must be verified by the qualifiedMin or qualifiedMax count

13.v: Minimum number of time that the shape indicated by sh:qualifiedValueShape must be found

14.v: Maximum number of times that the shape indicated by sh:qualifiedValueShape must be found

15.v: Possible list of shapes that the values of the predicate/path must conform to, expressed as a Turtle list

16.v: General URI or string pattern expected for the values of the predicate/path, expressed as a regex

17.v: Set to true for skos:prefLabel to indicate there should be only one value per langage

18.v: Expected possible values for the predicate/path, when the list is small and known in advance. Expressed as a Turtle list

19.v: List of langage codes expected for this predicate/path. Expressed as a turtle list

20.v: Set to true if the property must be unique per language

5.v: Questions / Comments (internal, not converted to SHACL)

4.v: The first name of the person
The last name of the person
